snippet.textDisplay:
Brian, you've made a grave mistake! The coin prices in Superstar Saga weren't for Mushroom Kingdom coins. They were for Beanbean Kingdom coins! To make matters even more complicated, the exchange rate between Mushroom coins and Beanbean coins was wildly different at two different points in the game. The first time you're told what the exchange rate is, it's 100 Mushroom coins for every 10 Beanbean coins, or 10:1, which is pretty easy to calculate. However, the second time, about halfway through the game after your fight with Queen Bean, Toadsworth tells you that the current value of 99,999,999,999,999 Mushroom coins is 99 Beanbean coins, for an INSANE exchange rate of 1,010,101,010,101:1. This is implies one of two scenarios. The first is that the value of Beanbean coins skyrocketed during that brief time. The second, and more likely scenario, is that, during that same window of time, the Mushroom Kingdom underwent a total economic collapse. This was likely due to the fallout from Princess Peach (who was actually Birdo in disguise while the real Peach was in hiding but that's neither here nor there) having her voice replaced with an "explosive vocabulary" by Cackletta and Fawful, effectively leaving them without a ruler.


Basically what i'm trying to say is that, unless the Mushroom Kingdom economy recovered after Peach was reinstated, our boy Mario is probably fucked. That is, unless he retires to the Beanbean Kingdom instead, but customs were already pretty tight IIRC. In his old age, he might not be able to pass the border jump game required to let you into the Kingdom.

snippet.textDisplay:
I love you BDG. But I feel like this video COULD come across as "finance is hopeless". It is not.


Anyone feeling on edge about this stuff should do yourselves a favor and take a chill trip to r/personalfinance. They're a lovely bunch and you'll learn a lot. They'll set you right on your way.


It can take some mathematical thinking to fully grasp finance, so many people are too scared to think about it. The thing is, you don't ACTUALLY need to understand it to follow the best practices. Learn the basic rules, and stick to them.


This video makes it seem impossible (largely because you use inflation for your costs but not your salary, and you aren't investing your savings to let them grow, so inflation just eats them). It's not impossible, but it takes discipline and sacrifice, and starting as early as possible changes EVERYTHING.


GL out there friends <3

I love you BDG. But I feel like this video COULD come across as "finance is hopeless". It is not.


Anyone feeling on edge about this stuff should do yourselves a favor and take a chill trip to r/personalfinance. They're a lovely bunch and you'll learn a lot. They'll set you right on your way.


It can take some mathematical thinking to fully grasp finance, so many people are too scared to think about it. The thing is, you don't ACTUALLY need to understand it to follow the best practices. Learn the basic rules, and stick to them.


This video makes it seem impossible (largely because you use inflation for your costs but not your salary, and you aren't investing your savings to let them grow, so inflation just eats them). It's not impossible, but it takes discipline and sacrifice, and starting as early as possible changes EVERYTHING.


GL out there friends <3
